<div class="indented"><a id="comment-11718"></a>
  <div class="comment">
    <h3 class="title"><a href="/peril-facebook-anti-privacy-pattern#comment-11718" class="active">This is not the danger of walled gardens</a></h3>    <div class="submitted">Submitted by <a href="/user/brad" title="View user profile." rel="nofollow">brad</a> on Wed, 2010-05-12 00:05.</div>
    <div class="content"><p>Strangely, this is about the danger of open gardens, but in this case I mean ones that make their user&#8217;s data open to public access.  As long as sites that do that can get an edge on sites that constrain themselves to protect user rights, there will be competitive pressure to not protect user rights.</p>

<p>This is hard to combat.  On PCs, the spyware concept arose because what the spyware products did was even more deceptive than this, and it was easy for users to understand it and want to fight it.</p>

<p>The new, privacy-invading competitors will not get business from those who are highly privacy conscious, but they don&#8217;t need them at first.  They only need them later.  But they can grow and be a threat without them, and then use other leverage to bring them along.</p>
</div>
